===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} as "square-headed bolt for a crossbow" c.1225, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|quarel|lang=fro}} (modern French {{term|carreau|lang=fr}}), from {{etyl|VL.|en}} ''*quadrellus'', the diminutive of {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|quadrus||a square|lang=la}}, related to [[quattuor]] "four".

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[diamond]]-shaped piece of coloured [[glass]] forming part of a stained glass window.
# A [[square]] [[tile]]; [[quarry tile]].
# A square-headed [[arrow]] for a [[crossbow]].
#* '''1600''', Edward Fairfax, The ''Jerusalem Delivered'' of Tasso, Book VII, ciii:
#*: ''Twanged the string, out flew the '''quarrel''' long,''
#*:: ''And through the subtle air did singing pass.''
#* Sir J. Mandeville
#*: to shoot with arrows and '''quarrel'''
#* Sir Walter Scott
#*: two arblasts, {{...}} with windlaces and '''quarrels'''
#* '''1829'''. The Olio; or, Museum of Entertainment, page 174
#*: ''[The small cross-bow] was carried by the foot-soldiers, and when used was charged with a '''quarrel''' or bar-bolt, that is, a small arrow with a flat head''
#* '''2000'''. George R. R. Martin, ''[[wikipedia:A Storm of Swords|A Storm of Swords, Part 2]]'', page 379
#*: ''Satin scooped up his crossbow and sent a few '''quarrel'''s after them as they ran, to see them off the faster.''
# A small [[opening]] in [[window]] [[tracery]], of which the [[cusp]]s etc. make the form nearly square.
# A four-sided cutting tool or [[chisel]] with a diamond-shaped end.

